\end{align*} Adding the first two congruences, we get \[3ab+2bc+2ca\equiv 6abc\pmod{13}.\] Subtracting the third congruence from this last one, we get \[ab\equiv 0\pmod{13}.\] Since $a,b<13$, we must have $a=0$ or $b=0$. However, $a,b$ are positive integers, so we must have $ab\neq 0$. Therefore, there are no solutions to the system of congruences, and the remainder when $a+b+c$ is divided by $13$ can be any of the integers $1,2,\ldots,12$. The answer is any integer from 1 to 12, inclusive.

